 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h1><p>Once =
cascade layouts are setup the rest is simple raymarching. For each pixel wi=
thin our cascade we calculate that pixel=E2=80=99s ray index and probe inde=
x associated with that pixel in our cascade. Calculating the ray index is s=
imple, we take the pixel=E2=80=99s relative X,Y position within the probe a=
nd convert it to a one-dimensional index:</p><pre><code>probeX =3D pixel.x =
% probeWidth;
probeY =3D pixel.y % probeHeight;
ray_index =3D probeY * probeWidth + probeX;</code></pre><p>Once we know the=
 ray index calculating the angle is as easy as dividing the index by the to=
tal ray count within the probe which is probeWidth x probeHeight, then mult=
iply by 2PI for the angle in radians:</p><pre><code>ray_count =3D probeWidt=
h * probeHeight;
ray_angle =3D ray_index / ray_count * PI * 2;</code></pre><p><span>The last=
 and final part is satisfying the linear resolution by calculating the leng=
th of the ray and how far away the ray should be cast using </span><a href=
=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DiNEE2ghW19A" rel=3D"">geometric seque=
nces</a><span> (generates a number series with a common scaling factor):</s=
pan></p><pre><code>// Calculate the interval length/start using geometric s=
equences.
origin =3D (interval * (1 - pow(4, cascadeIndex))) / (1 - 4);
length =3D interval * pow(4, cascadeIndex);</code></pre><p>Here the term =
=E2=80=9Cinterval,=E2=80=9D is the initial length of rays in the lowest cas=
cade, cascade0. All of the cascades scale off of the initial settings of ca=
scade0, spacing, angular resolution and starting ray length (interval). Not=
ice how the origin moves 4x further away as we increase the cascade index f=
rom 0=E2=80=A6N by a power or factor of 4. Going back to tmpvar=E2=80=99s p=
layground we can see a visualization of the interval scaling.</p><div class=
